PHILOSOPHICAL FRAMEWORKS ATTRIBUTION

The coaching frameworks referenced in this project draw from the following
public domain and open traditions:

- The Bhagavad Gita, Upanishads, and Advaita Vedanta tradition (public domain)
- Swami Vivekananda's works (public domain — pre-1928)
- Sri Aurobindo's writings (public domain in many jurisdictions; verify locally)
- Samarth Ramdas's Dasabodha (public domain)
- Maharshi Dayananda's works (public domain)
- Jnana Prabodhini's pedagogical philosophy (referenced with attribution;
  contact Jnana Prabodhini for permissions regarding institutional use)

The following frameworks are adapted under fair use for educational purposes:
- VIA Character Strengths (inspired by Peterson & Seligman, 2004)
- PERMA model (Seligman, 2011)
- Adaptive Leadership framework (Heifetz & Linsky)
- Immunity to Change (Kegan & Lahey)
- Positive Intelligence / Saboteur framework (Chamine)
- Getting Things Done principles (David Allen)

This project does not claim ownership of any of these frameworks. Users seeking
to use these frameworks in commercial coaching practices should consult the
original sources for licensing requirements.

---

PSYCHOMETRIC ASSESSMENTS DISCLAIMER

The psychometric assessments in `intake/apps/` are designed for coaching
self-reflection purposes only. They are not clinically validated instruments
and should not be used for clinical assessment, hiring decisions, or any
purpose requiring validated psychometric tools. For clinical or research
applications, use validated instruments from qualified publishers.
